[In the thread "Symbols of War," we discussed Jane Fonda and Lt. William Calley, and how, unfortunately, they came to represent the two sides of our nation's internal struggle over the war in Vietnam.] <p> I've tried to make it very clear that I don't think EITHER of them is a good representative.  In fact, the whole process of using individuals,
and individual acts to represent larger systemic processess, is inherently misleading.  
<p>
It may be necessary in a certain sense--storytelling is a natural form of human understanding--but what we are talking about in this case is a deeply impoverished, highly attenuated form of storytelling--just a single scene, really, and not a real story at all. 
<p>
If we must focus on individuals, then rather than focusing on Calley, we should focus on [former Secretary of Defense Robert] McNamara for the early part of the war, and [former Secretary of State Henry] Kissinger for the later part.  They were morally responsible, and they have been largely excused, but it was THEIR actions which were responsible for the unprecedented destruction wrought in Vietnam.  
<p>
The larger story of these two men would take us into a much more fruitful direction for analysis, since it would illuminate the complex of assumptions, values and forces operating at the elite levels of society that actually directed our national politics -- of which the Vietnam War was but one example.
<p>
Had it not been for widespread resistence by ordinary people, the war would have gone on, no matter what the cost, because the elites--people like McNamara and Kissinger--willed it so.  
<p>
Many of us opposed to the war saw it very clearly in these terms -- the elites prosecuting a war versus the people in whose name it was being waged, but who had NEVER been consulted, who had NEVER even been told the basic facts so that they COULD have been meaningfully consulted. Thus, opposition to the war was very much a matter of affirmation of democracy.
<p>
So long as the war is represented in terms of GIs versus protesters, it is misrepresented, not least because opposition to the war finally became very widespread among GI themselves. So long as the war is represented in terms of Calley vs. Fonda, it is misrepresented, not least because Calley himself was an involuntary victim of the war's dehumanization before he became a war criminal.  
<p>
Behind the evil that he did lies a deeper, more fundamental AND FREELY CHOSEN evil -- the evil of men like McNamara and Kissinger.  They are the real war criminals, and their class is the real criminal class. Their ideas did not then, and do not now include a true democratic dialogue to determine course of our nation in times of war or peace.
<p>
