Paul,<p>
I have to weigh in as an opponent of this view. To call McNamara a "war criminal" and place him with the likes of Goebbels, et al, is to perpetuate attitudes that will get us into more Vietnams.  Do you honestly think McNamara was sitting there thinking of ways to deceive the American people because he WANTED to fight a war? No way, Jose.  The man may not have fully accepted his responsibility for the tragic mistake that was 'Nam, he may not have given us the straight skinny in his book IN RETROSPECT, but he's no war criminal.  To demonize him and other bureaucrats and politicians is to perpetuate the same kind of objectification that we perpetuate on our "enemies".  
<p>
Consider:  McNamara comes into his position as a regular whiz kid, successful in the management of logisitics in World War II (which was a successful effort to turn back fascism), successful in corporate management, and full of belief in what Kennedy had to say about service and the evils of communism, belief that the Vietnamese couldn't possibly stand up to us any better than the Japanese or the Germans had. (There's the racism Renny mentioned in the "Why Were We There?" thread.)  Why WOULDN'T he think he could "turn back communism in Vietnam"?  
<p>
My point is that the man was operating from a particular (not evil) perspective, and until we understand that perspective, we have no right to condemn him.  The same holds true for Truman, who got reemed here earlier for not having the gumption to stand up to the French in 1945, or for Wilson who couldn't free the French colonies at the Treaty of Versailles.  Come on people! What did you expect?  That we'd risk stability in Europe for some candy-ass country nobody ever heard of?  For God's sake, try and walk a few steps in Truman's shoes at the end of WWII, or McNamara's shoes in the early '60s.  It's WAY too easy to look back and call these people "war criminals" and be done with it.
<p>
