Mike doesn't like me calling McNamara a war criminal.  He says this puts him in the same class with Goebbels.  That it objectifies and demonizes him, and this is the same thing that lead us into Vietnam. 
<p>
With all due respect, moral judgement REQUIRES finding people responsible.  If they DO evil, then they are RESPONSIBLE for evil.  
<p>
Judging them by their ACTIONS is NOTHING like judging people for the color of their skin.  Demonization is a PERVERSION and MOCKERY of moral judgement.  Attacking the excercise of moral judgement as being demonization simply furthers the paralysis of moral judgement.  Indeed, it is a form demonization in itself.
<p>
You don't have to be as bad as Jeffrey Dahmer to be a murderer, and you don't have to be as bad as Goebbels to be a war criminal.  All you have to do is commit war crimes.
<p>
McNamara *IS* a war criminal.  There is no doubt about this.  The entire conduct of the war, with massive civilian casualties as an integral, inescapable part of the war made the ENTIRE conduct of the war a war crime.  Those who were responsible for it were war criminals, PERIOD.  
<p>
This goes for the firebombing of Dresden, and the bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki as well.  Every time we take another step down that road, the next step becomes easier and easier.  You want your comparison with the Nazis, here it is: the Nazis didn't start out with the extermination of the Jews, they got there step-by-step, each step seemed "reasonable" at the time, at least to a large number of "good Germans".  Do we want to use THEIR excuse as our own?  
<p>
You suggest that we need to understand McNamara. Fine, understanding is great, I'm all for it.  It's why I'm here, after all.  But understanding a criminal does not excuse the crime.  It may help us to avoid future crimes, however. This is why it is VERY important to recognize it as a crime, and call it what is.  It's a PART of understanding.  Not all--just part, but a vital part without which all that remains is a lie, however truthful its particulars may be in themselves.  
<p>
Without truth-telling, we are DOOMED to repeat the crimes of the past. And then others will come after us and say, "Oh, you have to understand them, you can't blame them, there were all these *GOOD REASONS* for them to believe what they did."  And another cycle of barbarity will follow.
<p>
NO THANKS.  McNamara is a war criminal.  By their fruits ye shall know them.  If we do not reason backwards from the fruits, we will never come to recognize the roots of the evil that has been done in our names, and thus we will never be able to prevent such evil being done in the future.  We, too, shall be guilty of that future evil, because we had a chance to stop it before it began, but we failed to act.
<p>
At the same time, you go on to defend Truman and Wilson.  What did they do?  Simple.  They betrayed what America is SUPPOSED to stand for--especially our own Declaration of Independence which sustains the Vietnamese claim for self-determination.  Instead, they served the interests of the US as an imperial power -- and the US Empire is the foremost enemy of the US Republic.  There are two huge oceans protecting the US Republic from any conceivable enemy in the world--except the US Empire, which has us totally dominated, especially in our minds.
<p>
No one held a gun to Wilson's head and made him spout out all that idealistic BS at the Treaty of Versailles.  (BS because he didn't really believe it.) It was HIS idea to articulate those standards.  And Ho Chi Mihn had the umitigated gall to take him at his WORD!
<p>
You seem completely unaware of Wilson's racism, and how the ideology of democracy (as opposed to its reality) was used to justify exploitation at home and abroad by a "broad bipartisan consensus" beginning in the 1890s.
<p>
And we're supposed to give Wilson "a break"????
<p>
How about the Vietnamese???  How about giving THEM a break?
<p>
How about everyone who DIED in WWII, because the Treaty of Versailles was so based on vengeance, so little based on justice that WWII was a virtual inevitability?
<p>
I've got a secret, Mike.  NOBODY thinks of themselves as doing evil. Hitler didn't think he was a war criminal either.  EVERYONE has a very good reason for what they are doing--in fact it's often the case that the more criminal the action, the better the reason.
<p>
Democracy depends on critical reason.  On self-examination.  On questioning.  Men like Wilson, Truman, McNamara and Kissinger are NOT at heart men of democracy.  They are not keen on the Socratic life.  They are not fit citizens of a democracy, much less leaders.  So long as we are willing to let such men be our leaders, we do deep dishonor to the ideals on which our country is founded.  
<p>
They are high ideals, and we will always be falling short of them.  The test is how we respond when we fall short.  Do we examine ourselves and our mistakes and try to learn from them, or do we make excuses -- which are, after all, the foundations of tyranny.  Tyranny ALWAYS has "necessity" to excuse its actions.
<p>
