On Moral Judgement...<p>

I think the difference between McNamara and the American soldier in Vietnam is one of understanding and intent. McNamara had the information of the total reality of the war and had control of a part of the war, enough so that he was connscious of what he was doing. He knew what was going on and decided to continue to lead us forward (downward). The soldier on the ground was not given the information with which to fully understand what was going on. That information was often found in country or after a great deal of looking.
<p>
McNamara had the intent of destroying people, villages, innocents without regard to their humanity. The soldier killed in self-defense, often when the situation was a kill-or-be-killed situation. This is why the Nuremburg trials focused primarily on the leaders and not the soliders of WWII. I personally think that clarity of thought have something to do with it as well.
<p>
The Calley-type massacres, the mass killings, were a direct result of a situation that was nothing less than surreal. How else do we describe a situation where a sane person is expected to kill and kill and kill, day after day after day? Where every day becomes a contest in which winning is living? This reality was a soldier's reality and a mind-warping one, at that. McNamara didn't miss a meal, never slept outside of his fine hotel rooms and acted with total disregard of the humanity of a people.
<p>
I for one have no problem calling McNamara and his ilk war criminals and just as easily have no problems not making that judgement on the masses of soldiers involved in the pulling of triggers. Surprisingly enough, in 1970 when I met with several NLF [North Vietnamese] fighters, they are the ones who most clearly made this distinction to me. They said that they did not hold the American people responsible for the war, but did the leaders of our government.
<p>
PS--When McNamara released his book and asked for forgiveness I almost puked. Yes, he is closer to Goebbels than you or I. No forgiveness coming from me, that's for sure.
<p>
